🧠 ⚙️ Meaning Gap Detector (MGD v1.0)

Purpose:
Detect when felt meaning (F) is drifting from literal meaning (R)—in yourself or others.

⸻

🧩 Core Model
	•	R (Literal): What was actually said
	•	F (Felt): What it seems to mean
	•	Δ (Gap): Difference between them

Δ = F − R

Large Δ = higher chance of:
	•	misunderstanding
	•	projection
	•	hidden intent
	•	emotional distortion

⸻

🔍 Step-by-Step Detection (real-time)

1. 📄 Capture Literal (R)

Force yourself to restate:

“What was actually said, word-for-word?”

Keep it boring. No interpretation.

⸻

2. 🌡️ Identify Felt Meaning (F)

Ask:

“What does this feel like it means?”

Label it:
	•	tone (hostile, caring, dismissive)
	•	intent (attack, help, withdraw)

⸻

3. 📏 Measure the Gap (Δ)

Ask:

“How far apart are these?”

Quick scale:
	•	Δ ≈ 0 → aligned (clear communication)
	•	Δ small → mild interpretation
	•	Δ large → ⚠️ distortion or subtext

⸻

4. 🧪 Classify the Cause

When Δ is large, it’s usually one of these:

A. Internal distortion (you)
	•	mood
	•	past experience
	•	insecurity
	•	fatigue

👉 “Is this coming from me?”

⸻

B. External signal (them)
	•	tone mismatch
	•	sarcasm
	•	passive aggression
	•	hidden intent

👉 “Are they saying one thing, meaning another?”

⸻

C. Ambiguity (neutral gap)
	•	unclear wording
	•	missing context

👉 “This is just under-specified”

⸻

5. ⚖️ Action Selection

If Internal:

Recalibrate → trust R more than F

⸻

If External:

Probe gently:

	•	“Hey, what did you mean by that?”
	•	“Just to make sure I understood…”

⸻

If Ambiguous:

Clarify or wait for more data

⸻

🔥 Fast Mental Shortcut (in the moment)

You don’t need the full process every time.

Just run:

“What was said?” vs “What am I adding?”

That alone catches most errors.

⸻

🧠 Example (live breakdown)

Input:

“You’ve been busy lately.”

⸻

R:
	•	Statement about your time usage

F:
	•	“They’re annoyed”
	•	“I’m neglecting them”
	•	“I’m doing something wrong”

⸻

Δ:

Moderate to high

⸻

Check:
	•	Did they sound annoyed?
	•	Or am I inserting that?

⸻

Action:
	•	Either relax (internal distortion)
	•	Or ask (external signal)

⸻

